"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function in numpy divides the input by pi before applying the sinc function. When the input is an integer, sinc will be zero except when the input is zero, where sinc will be one. However, due to floating point precision issues, direct comparison of sinc_result with integers may fail. Also, np.sinc(1) is not exactly zero but close to it.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7c7\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_almost_equal(sinc_result[0], 1)\\n8c8\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_almost_equal(sinc_result[1], 0)\"\n}"